    id: "art-c15",
    title: "Gen Z Slang: A Survival Guide",
    content: "If you've ever talked to someone under 25 and felt completely lost, don't worry — even older native speakers struggle with Gen Z slang. This generation has created an entirely new vocabulary, largely influenced by social media, memes, and internet culture. Here's your survival guide.\n\nLet's start with the essentials. \"Slay\" means to do something exceptionally well. If your friend gives an amazing presentation, you'd say \"You slayed that!\" \"Bet\" is used to express agreement — it's basically \"okay\" or \"sounds good.\" \"Bussin\" means something is really good, especially food. \"This pasta is bussin\" means it's delicious.\n\n\"Sus\" comes from the game Among Us and means suspicious or shady. \"That guy seems sus\" means you don't trust him. \"Vibe check\" is assessing someone's mood or energy. If someone says \"vibe check\" they want to know how you're feeling right now.\n\n\"It's giving\" is followed by a description of the energy something projects. \"Your outfit is giving CEO\" means your outfit makes you look powerful and in charge. \"Rent-free\" means something is constantly on your mind — \"That song is living rent-free in my head.\"\n\nNow for some emotional expressions. \"I'm literally dead\" means something is extremely funny. \"I can't even\" expresses being overwhelmed — either by something funny, frustrating, or shocking. \"Periodt\" (with a T) means \"end of discussion\" — it emphasizes that what you just said is final and not up for debate.\n\n\"Stan\" means to be an extremely devoted fan of someone. It comes from the Eminem song of the same name. \"I stan that artist\" means you're a huge, dedicated fan. \"GOAT\" stands for \"Greatest Of All Time\" — high praise for anyone or anything.\n\nSome cautionary notes: \"Mid\" means mediocre or average, and calling something mid can be surprisingly insulting. \"Cringe\" describes something painfully embarrassing. \"Ratio\" is when a reply gets more likes than the original post, which is considered a public humiliation online.\n\nThe tricky thing about Gen Z slang is that it changes incredibly fast. Words that are popular today might be \"cheugy\" (outdated or uncool) by next month. The best approach is to understand these terms rather than force yourself to use them. If you're over 30 and start saying \"slay\" in every sentence, Gen Z will probably find that more cringe than cool.\n\nStay curious, stay humble, and remember — language evolves. Every generation creates its own slang. Today's \"slay\" is yesterday's \"groovy\" is last century's \"the bee's knees.\" It's all part of the beautiful chaos of living language.",
    contentZh: "如果你曾經跟 25 歲以下的人聊天，然後覺得完全聽不懂，別擔心——連年紀大一點的母語者都很難跟上 Z 世代的俚語。這個世代創造了全新的詞彙，很大程度上受到社群媒體、迷因和網路文化的影響。這是你的生存指南。\n\n先從必備詞彙開始。「Slay」意思是把某件事做得非常好。如果你的朋友做了一場精彩的簡報，你會說「You slayed that!（你超厲害！）」「Bet」用來表示同意——基本上就是「okay」或「sounds good」。「Bussin」表示某樣東西真的很好，尤其是食物。「This pasta is bussin」意思是這個義大利麵超好吃。\n\n「Sus」來自遊戲 Among Us，意思是可疑的或不光明正大的。「That guy seems sus」意思是你不信任他。「Vibe check」是評估某人的心情或能量。如果有人說「vibe check」，他們想知道你現在感覺怎麼樣。\n\n「It's giving」後面接一個描述，說明某樣東西散發出的氣場。「Your outfit is giving CEO」意思是你的穿著讓你看起來很有權威感。「Rent-free」表示某件事一直在你腦海中——「That song is living rent-free in my head（那首歌一直在我腦中揮之不去）。」\n\n現在來看一些情感表達。「I'm literally dead」表示某件事超級好笑。「I can't even」表達被壓倒的感覺——不管是因為好笑、沮喪還是震驚的事。「Periodt」（帶一個 T）意思是「討論到此結束」——強調你剛說的話是最終結論，不接受辯論。\n\n「Stan」意思是成為某人的極度忠實粉絲。它來自 Eminem 同名的歌曲。「I stan that artist」意思是你是一個超級死忠粉絲。「GOAT」代表「Greatest Of All Time（史上最偉大）」——對任何人或任何事的最高讚美。\n\n一些需要注意的：「Mid」表示平庸或普通，說某樣東西 mid 可能出乎意料地具有侮辱性。「Cringe」描述某件事令人痛苦地尷尬。「Ratio」是指回覆的讚數比原帖還多，在網路上這被視為一種公開的羞辱。\n\nZ 世代俚語棘手的地方在於它變化得非常快。今天流行的詞彙到下個月可能就變成「cheugy」（過時的或不酷的）了。最好的方法是理解這些詞彙，而不是強迫自己使用它們。如果你超過 30 歲然後每句話都說「slay」，Z 世代可能會覺得那比酷更 cringe。\n\n保持好奇，保持謙遜，記住——語言會演化。每個世代都會創造自己的俚語。今天的「slay」就是昨天的「groovy」，就是上個世紀的「the bee's knees」。這都是活的語言美麗混亂的一部分。",
